<H3> <TI>   Experimental Study of Optical Pulse Propagation Through </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Experimental Study of Optical Pulse Propagation Through </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Clouds 

<F P=102>   947N0046B Moscow IZVESTIYA AKADEMII NAUK FIZIKA ATMOSFERY I 
OKEANA in Russian Vol. 30, No. 1, Jan.-Feb. 94, pp. 39-45 </F>

<F P=103> 947N0046B </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA AKADEMII NAUK FIZIKA ATMOSFERY I 
OKEANA </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by V. A. Korshunov, L. N. Pavlova, N. P. Romanov, </F>
and V. S. Shuklin; Typhoon Scientific Production Association; 
manuscript submitted 17 Mar 93; UDC 551.521.3:551.576.1] 
  [Abstract] Amplitude-time responses were measured for 
optical pulses vertically propagated through stratified clouds. 
ATR measurements were complemented by a sounding of the optical 
and microphysical parameters of the cloud cover. The experiments 
were carried out in the fall of 1988 and the spring of 1989 in 
the area around the Typhoon Production Association's 
high-altitude weather station near Obninsk. Twelve series of 
measurements under different types of cloud cover were carried 
out. The laser radiation source was carried on board an 
Ilyushin-14 aircraft and had a wavelength of 0.532 Êm, a beam 
divergence of 10Î, a pulse length of 10 ns, and a repetition 
rate of 10 Hz. The plane, which flew above the clouds at an 
altitude of 2-4 km, was guided to the observation point by a 
Meteorite-2 meteorological radar station. The propagated 
radiation was recorded by a ground-based 4-channel lens system 
with a focal length of 160-300 mm, an aperture diameter of 120 
mm, and receiving angles set at 5 and 20Î. The time 
resolution of the transmission/receiving system equaled 30 ns. 
Comparison of the ATR data with numerical calculations performed 
using the Monte Carlo method showed that a cloud stratification 
model constructed as a set of homogeneous layers with a 
scattering indicatrix typical for stratified clouds allowed for 
a satisfactory interpretation of the experimental data. The 
fundamental parameter determining ATR is the optical thickness 
of the cloud cover. The variations in ATR observed for different 
optical thicknesses (_t_ Û 25) were attributed to the 
combined 
effects of various geometrical parameters such as distance from 
source to receiver, cloud ceiling altitude, thickness of the 
cloud strata, and so forth. Figures 4, tables 2; references 12: 
7 Russian, 5 Western. 

</TEXT>

