<H3> <TI>   Unique Characteristics of Radiation Scattering by </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unique Characteristics of Radiation Scattering by </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Nonspherical   Particles of Atmospheric Aerosol 

<F P=102> 947N0046C Moscow IZVESTIYA AKADEMII NAUK FIZIKA ATMOSFERY I 
OKEANA in Russian, Vol. 30 No. 1, Jan.-Feb. 94, pp. 46-52 </F>

<F P=103> 947N0046C </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA AKADEMII NAUK FIZIKA ATMOSFERY I 
OKEANA </F>

<F P=105>  Russian, </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N. V. Voshchinnikov and V. G. Farafonov; St. </F>
Petersburg University and St. Petersburg Institute of Aviation 
Instrument Manufacturing; manuscript submitted 29 Dec 92; 
resubmitted after revision 5 May 93; UDC 551.593] 
  [Abstract] A precise theory of light scattering by 
spheroidal particles was used to study the unique 
characteristics of radiation scattering by atmospheric aerosol. 
The new method utilizes the separation of variables to solve the 
problem of electromagnetic plane wave diffraction by a 
homogeneous spheroid and is considerably more efficient from a 
computational standpoint than the method devised by Asano and 
Yamamoto. The expressions for scattered radiation intensity are 
elaborated within the framework of a rigorous solution for both 
severely oblate and severely prolate spheroids. Numerical 
results obtained for ice particles with different shapes and 
wave lengths of 10.6 Êm are discussed. On the basis of the 
adduced calculations, it was concluded that the average light 
scattering indicatrix is smoother for oblate than for prolate 
particles. As a rule, the albedo of the oblate particles was 
somewhat greater than for prolate particles of the same volume. 
Changing the imaginary part of the index of refraction for the 
substance of the particles has virtually no bearing on the 
behavior of the normalized functions of the scattering 
indicatrix, but does affect the magnitude of the particle 
albedo. The polarization of the scattered radiation varies 
markedly with changes in particle shape. However, in some cases, 
prolate spheroids could be substituted for infinite circular 
cylinders. The findings of this study provide a basis for 
conducting optical atmospheric sounding experiments that would 
make it possible to determine the degree of sphericity of the 
scattering particles and their spatial orientation. Figures 4, 
tables 2; references 26: 18 Russian, 8 Western. 

</TEXT>

