<H3> <TI>   Cloning of Recurrent Oxytocin Gene Sequence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cloning of Recurrent Oxytocin Gene Sequence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   947C0050C Moscow BIOORGANICHESKAYA KHIMIYA in Russian Vol. 
19 No. 6, Jun. 95 pp. 629-632 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0050C </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow BIOORGANICHESKAYA KHIMIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by A.I. Gurevich, T.A. Kachalina, A.L. Kayushin, </F>
M.D. Korosteleva, A.I. Miroshnikov, Bioorganic Chemistry 
Institute imeni M.M. Shemyakin and Yu.A. Ovchinnikov at Russia's 
Academy of Sciences, Moscow; UDC 547.963.32.057:577.213.3] 
  [Abstract] The difficulty of chemical enzymatic synthesis 
and cloning of artificial oligomer genes of short peptides, 
e.g., oxytocin, by traditional methods, probably due to the fact 
that recurrent sequences in DNA may cause varying recombinant 
restructuring, prompted attempts to use different codons in the 
synthesized structures in order to diminish the homology of 
individual polynucleotide segments for encoding the same amino 
acids. To this end, a vector obtained by splitting the pFPCP10 
plasmid by the BamHI and EcoRI restrictase 
was used for cloning the B/E gene and a vector 
obtained by splitting the pTE2IL3 plasmid by the 
HindIII and EcoRI restrictase was used for 
cloning the H/E gene. Deletions caused by ruptures in 
one of the plasmid DNA chains were noted in the experiment to 
clone a synthetic oxytocin trimer gene; it is stressed that 
these deletions are much less frequent when cloning a 
covalent-closed cyclical two-stranded DNA. These recurrent gene 
sequence cloning feature may also be observed in other cases. It 
is speculated that the difficulties related to these deletions 
or recombinations could be overcome by using the techniques 
which were verified in this study. Figures 2; references 7: 4 
Russian, 3 Western. 


</TEXT>

