<H3> <TI>   Production of Monoclonal Antibodies to Digoxin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Production of Monoclonal Antibodies to Digoxin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   947C0130D Moscow BIOTEKHNOLOGIYA in Russian No. 4, Apr. 93 
pp. 38-40 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0130D </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow BIOTEKHNOLOGIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N.P. Danilova, S.A. Yazynin, S.N. Yeremenko, </F>
R.G. Vasilov, Scientific Production Association of 
Biotechnology, Moscow; UDC 616.097] 
  [Abstract] The popularity of immunoassay methods for 
medicinal monitoring of digoxin and reports about the presence 
of the so-called digoxin-like immunoreactive factor in the serum 
of some patients who receive no digoxin due to the 
cross-reactions with endogenic steroids as well as the desire to 
obtain monoclonal antibodies to digoxin prompted an attempt to 
produce antibodies to digoxin suitable for this drug's 
immunoassay study. To this end, digoxin was attached through the 
digitoxose terminal radical to the bovine serum albumin and 
hemocyanin; the conjugates and their properties are described. 
BALB/c mice were immunized intraperitoneally and subcutaneously 
by 0.2 ml of emulsion. The hybridomata producing MCAs were 
produced by fusing spleen cells of BALB/c mice immunized by the 
conjugate with X-63 Ag 8.568 myeloma cells, and three hybrid 
clones were selected by indirect solid-phase enzyme immunoassay 
analysis method (ELISA). The antibodies were obtained from the 
mice's ascitic tumors, purified, and analyzed. The procedure for 
determining the antibodies' specificity and affinity is 
outlined. The findings confirm that monoclonal antibodies to the 
digoxin drug with a high affinity and specificity and with a 
binding constant ranging from 10[.sup]9[/] to 
9.2[.sup].[/]10[.sup]9[/] M[.sup]-1[/] were produced. 
Figures 2; tables 1; references: 14 Western. 


</TEXT>

