<H3> <TI>   Isolation and Amino-Acid Composition of Peptides Formed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Isolation and Amino-Acid Composition of Peptides Formed </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
By   Cleaving Penicillium vitale Catalase With 
Staphylococcus Proteinase 

<F P=102> 947C0254A Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA in Russian Vol. 9, No. 
3, May-June 1993 pp. 38-42 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0254A </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N. V. Latyshko, T. L. Levitina, O. S. </F>
Miroshnichenko, L. V. Gudkova, E. A. Kozlov; UDC 577.112.5] 
  [Abstract] A solution of dry P. vitale catalase 
and 0.2 n NaOH was separated through dialysis in 0.1 n 
NH4HCO3 overnight at 8ÎC. Miles 
(England) staphylococcus proteinase was added to the dialyzate, 
which was then allowed to stand for 6 h at 37ÎC. The 
resulting sediment was centrifuged off, and the process liquid 
lyophilized. A total of 38 peptides were isolated through gel 
filtration on a Pharmacia (Sweden) G-50 sephadex, ion-exchange 
chromatography using Toyo-Soda (Japan) DEAE resin and Filtrak 
(Germany) FN-17 paper, and high-voltage electrophoresis using 
Filtrak (Germany) FN-17 paper. The amino-acid composition was 
determined with an AAA-339 analyzer made in the Czech Republic. 
Dansylation was used for N-end analysis. The peptides contained 
a total of 578 amino acids constituting 83% of the 
catalase's 
peptide chain, which has 670 amino acid residues according to 
x-ray crystallography data. Figures 3, tables 1; references 8: 6 
Russian, 2 Western. 


</TEXT>

