<H3> <TI>   Effect of Ionizing Radiation on Protein-Lipid Liposome </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Effect of Ionizing Radiation on Protein-Lipid Liposome </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Complexes 

<F P=102>   947C0254B Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA in Russian Vol. 9, No. 
3, May-June 1993 pp. 45-48 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0254B </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by V. I. Dreval; UDC 577.391] </F>
  [Abstract] The effect of ionizing radiation on 
protein-lipid liposome complexes with ferrihemoglobin and 
ferricytochrome C was studied. Vesicular membranes were obtained 
by extracting phospholipids from chicken egg yolks and exposing 
the suspension to ultrasound. The ferrihemoglobin was obtained 
by oxidizing human oxyhemoglobin with potassium ferricyanide and 
then gel-filtrating it on a G-25 molselect. The ferrihemoglobin 
and the ferricytochrome C were bound to the liposomes using a 
buffer and gel-filtrated on a G-200 sephadex. Protein 
concentration was registered on a SF-46 spectrophotometer at 750 
nm. The concentration of peroxidation products was found from 
their reaction with 2-thiobarbituric acid and expressed in terms 
of MDA (malonic dialdehyde) concentration per 1 mg of membrane 
lipid. Irradiation was performed on a linear accelerator with an 
electron energy of 5 MeV at doses of 10, 50, 100, 1000, 5,000, 
and 10,000 gR. The data obtained were processed using Student's 
t-statistic and the correlation coefficient, r, on an 
Iskra-1030 computer. It was found that the irradiation reduced 
Soret band intensity, a finding that is consistent with previous 
data, and induced structural changes in the proteins. 
Calculations performed for the binding constant, binding 
locations, and change in free energy revealed that the 
irradiation induced peroxidation of the lipids in the liposomes 
and altered the structure of the ferrihemoglobin, causing 
instability in the protein-lipid interactions. It was theorized 
that the lipid component plays a key role in this instability. 
Figures 2, tables 1; references 22: 17 Russian, 5 Western. 


</TEXT>

