<H3> <TI>   Structural-Functional Characterization of pBS195 Plasmid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Structural-Functional Characterization of pBS195 Plasmid </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
With   Broad Range of Gram-Positive and Gram-Negative Hosts 

<F P=102> 947C0126C Moscow MOLEKULYARNAYA GENETIKA, MIKROBIOLOGIYA I 
VIRUSOLOGIYA in Russian No. 4, July-Aug. 93 pp. 22-27 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0126C </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOLEKULYARNAYA GENETIKA, MIKROBIOLOGIYA I 
VIRUSOLOGIYA </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Ye.V. Kozlova, Ye.S. Suvorova, T.V. Pivovarenko, </F>
V.P. Romanov, A.M. Boronin, Institute of Microorganism 
Biochemistry and Physiology at Russia's Academy of Sciences, 
Pushchino; UDC 579.843.21:579] 
  [Abstract] Interest in lactobacilli and their applications 
in the food industry, medicine, and agriculture prompted a study 
of lactobacilli plasmids from the viewpoint of their development 
of properties and traits as well as their use as potential 
cloning vectors. To this end, the structural and functional 
properties of the pBS195 plasmid, including physical and genetic 
mapping, are examined, and the protein products determined by 
the pBS195 plasmid are studied. The ability of the pBS195 
plasmid to coexist with a broad range of hosts, both 
gram-positive and gram-negative, is noted, and the areas 
containing the kanamycin and oriV resistance genes are 
localized. The study reveals no homology of the kanamycin 
resistance determinants of the pBS195 plasmid with the 
determinants which control aminoglycoside of types I and II 
phosphotransferase and type II nucleotidyl transferase. It is 
speculated that in contrast to other plasmids, the pBS195 
contains a rep-system homologous with pUC19 which supports it in 
E. coli cells. Two 26 and 34 kD protein products were 
discovered by electrophoretic separation in the system of 
E. coli X295 minicells containing the pBS195 plasmid. 
The oxygenase activity determined by the pBS195 plasmid is 
discussed, and it is noted that enzyme is unusually 
substrate-specific and highly active in E. coli cells 
determined by the pBS195 plasmid. The plasmid shares homology 
with the nahC gene in the EcoRI-BamHI region. It is emphasized 
that the functional role of the oxygenase determined by the 
pBS195 for the host cells remains unclear. Figures 5; tables 3; 
references 30: 5 Russian, 25 Western. 


</TEXT>

