<H3> <TI>   Dominant Selectable Gene Transfer Using Retroviral </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dominant Selectable Gene Transfer Using Retroviral </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Vectors:   Simple and Quick Method to Produce Hybridomata Hybrids 

<F P=102> 947C0126E Moscow MOLEKULYARNAYA GENETIKA, MIKROBIOLOGIYA I 
VIRUSOLOGIYA in Russian No. 4, July-Aug. 93 pp. 31-34 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0126E </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOLEKULYARNAYA GENETIKA, MIKROBIOLOGIYA I 
VIRUSOLOGIYA </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by I.K. Fomin, I.I. Tikhonov, V.S. Prasolov, N.N. </F>
Voytenok, Hematology and Blood Transfusion Institute at the 
Belarussian Republic Ministry of Public Health and Molecular 
Biology Institute at Russia's Academy of Sciences, Moscow; UDC 
577.21] 
  [Abstract] The antibodies whose structure contains the 
molecules of two different antigen-specific segments--the 
so-called bispecific antibodies--and which are capable of 
cross-binding of molecules and cells and the methods of 
producing bispecific antibodies by fusing two hybridoma lines 
are discussed, and two approaches to fusing hybridomata 
producing monoclonal antibodies (MKA) to the _a_-tumor necrosis 
factor (FNO-_a_) and inorganic pyrophosphatase (NPF) of 
Escherichia coli are discussed. In one instance, a 
G418-stable hypoxanthine, aminopterine, thymidine (GAT) 
medium-sensitive partner was hybridized with a ``wild type'' 
partner while in another, various markers of antibiotic 
stability were introduced into both partner with the help of 
recombinant retroviral vectors. As a result, quadromata 
producing bispecific antibodies were produced by two methods 
whereby the quadromata formation efficiency was roughly the same 
in each case. The findings show that the use of retroviral 
vectors is a faster and simpler way of cell labeling. The method 
of hybridoma cell labeling with the help of retroviral vectors 
carrying dominant selectable genes of resistance to hygromycin B 
and genecytin (G418) has virtually no limitations. Figures 1; 
tables 2; references: 9 Western. 


</TEXT>

