<H3> <TI>   Use of Hemosorption to Correct Hemostasis in Diabetic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Use of Hemosorption to Correct Hemostasis in Diabetic </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Gangrene   Patients 

<F P=102> 937C0413F Minsk ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE BELARUSI in Russian No. 2, 
Feb 93 pp. 54-58 </F>

<F P=103> 937C0413F </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE BELARUSI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by A.V. Prokhorov, N.Ye. Bolotina, Surgery </F>
Department of the Moscow Medical Institute; UDC 
616.379-008.64:617.58-002.4]:615.246.2+615.38] 
  [Abstract] Recent studies showing the important role of 
hemostatic and hemorheologic impairments in the pathogenesis of 
diabetic angiopathy and the development of purulent necrotic 
lesions in the lower extremities in diabetic patients prompted 
an examination of the efficacy of hemosorption in treating 
diabetic gangrene patients and an attempt to ascertain its role 
in correcting the hemostatic disorders of blood circulation. To 
this end, 159 diabetic patients with trophic and purulent 
necrotic foot and calf lesions were observed, and 18 male and 12 
female patients were examined. Diagnostic tests were used for 
analyzing the hemostatic system. Extracorporeal hemosorption was 
conducted together with conservative therapy which included 
carbohydrate metabolism correction by means of subcutaneous 
insulin injection and hemo- and rheocorrector treatment, 
antibacterial and immunotherapy, etc. Hemosorption facilitated 
an increase in the anticoagulant and fibrinolytic plasma 
activity and improved peripheral circulation, making it possible 
to expand indications for ``minor'' foot amputations and lower 
the number of high amputations to 13.3%. On average, the 
use of 
complex therapy with hemosorption shortened the diabetic ulcer 
preparation by 5-7 days. Figures 3; references 8: 7 Russian, 1 
Western. 


</TEXT>

