<F P=100> LIFE SCIENCES </F>
<F P=101> MEDICINE AND PUBLIC HEALTH </F>
<H3> <TI>   Effect of Chronic Exposure to Low Levels of Combined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Effect of Chronic Exposure to Low Levels of Combined </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
External   and Incorporeal Ionizing Radiation on the Reproductive 
Capability of Male and Female CC57W Mice 

<F P=102> 947C0254C Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA in Russian Vol. 9, No. 
3, May-June 1993 pp. 49-52 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0254C </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev BIOPOLIMERY I KLETKA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by M. P. Stolina; UDC 575.16] </F>
  [Abstract] CC57W male and female mice from the Chernobyl 
and Kiev experimental populations were exposed to low levels of 
ionizing radiation to determine its effect on reproductive 
functioning. The radiation exposure for the test (Chernobyl) 
group was an order of magnitude or more higher than for the 
control (Kiev) group. The external _g_-background radiation 
exposure in the special 30-km vivarium at the Chernobyl nuclear 
power plant fluctuated between 70 to 100 mkR/h. Internal 
radiation exposure was effected by means of radionuclides 
inhaled or otherwise ingested by the mice. Crossbreeding of mice 
three to five months old was done at the Kiev vivarium 
(Institute of Molecular Biology and Genetics of the Ukrainian 
Academy of Sciences) within three days after exposure. The 
effect of the radiation exposure was studied by testing for the 
incidence of embryonic mortality in the offspring of the 
experimental and control groups. Pregnant females were dissected 
on the 16th, 17th, or 18th day of gestation, and the incidence 
of pre- and post-implantation mortality was determined from the 
number of yellow masses in the ovaries and from the intrauterine 
implantation and live embryo locations. A consistently high 
incidence of pre-implantation mortality was found in the 
offspring of three generations of female mice and of two 
generations of male mice from the Chernobyl population, an 
obvious consequence of the mutagenic effect of low doses of 
combined radiation on the gametes. This finding was further 
corroborated by the normal incidence of pre-implantation 
mortality among the offspring of the F3-males from 
the Chernobyl population, which were allowed to reach sexual 
maturity without exposure to radiation. Tables 2; references 12: 
6 Russian, 6 Western. 


