<H3> <TI>   Comparative Antimicrobial Activity of Chlorhexidin, </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comparative Antimicrobial Activity of Chlorhexidin, </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Decamethoxin,   and Septonex 

<F P=102> 937C0413D Minsk ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE BELARUSI in Russian No. 2, 
Feb. 93 pp. 40-42 </F>

<F P=103> 937C0413D </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE BELARUSI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by M.P. Korolevich, O.P. Sobeshchuk, A.A. </F>
Adarchenko, Clinical Pharmacology Course and Intrahospital 
Infection Laboratory at the Minsk Medical Institute; UDC 
576.8.088.3:615.28] 
  [Abstract] The urgency of combatting purulent infection 
using various antibacterial preparations and antiseptics which 
have a number of advantages over antibiotics and the arbitrary 
and empirical manner in which antiseptics are often prescribed 
necessitated a comparative study of the antimicrobial activity 
of chlorhexidin, decamethoxin, and septonex relative to hospital 
strains of Staphylococcus aureus, Pseudomonas 
aeruginosa and pathogenic forms of the enterobacteria 
species. Sensitivity to antiseptics was measured by diluting the 
preparations in a dense nutrient medium and establishing the 
minimum inhibiting concentration (MIK) for each strain. An 
analysis shows that in therapeutic concentrations, chlorhexidin, 
decamethoxin, and septonex inhibit the growth of all hospital 
strains of S. aureus and 48-78% of hospital strains 
of enterobacteria. Yet all hospital strains of P. 
aeruginosa are tolerant to decamethoxin and septonex while 
28.0% is tolerant to chlorhexidin. The conclusion is 
drawn that 
the use of the above antiseptics against hospital infections 
should be based on studies of the microorganisms' sensitivity to 
these preparations. Tables 1; references 7. 


</TEXT>

